definitions: not producing a definite result or final answer that settles a matter
examples: The test results were inconclusive about the cause
Their inconclusive debate left everyone more confused

definitions: lacking harmony or compatibility with surroundings or other elements in a situation
examples: His formal suit looked incongruous at the beach party
The modern building seemed incongruous among historic houses

definitions: having little or no importance, significance, or impact on outcomes
examples: She dismissed his comments as inconsequential to the decision
The error was inconsequential and didn't affect results

definitions: not staying the same throughout or not in agreement with something else
acting or done differently at different times without apparent reason
examples: His story was inconsistent with the evidence presented
The witness gave inconsistent testimonies during questioning
Her inconsistent performance made her unreliable for competitions
The weather has been inconsistent all week long

definitions: not clearly visible or attracting attention by being unobtrusive or modest
examples: She wore inconspicuous clothing to blend into crowds
The camera was placed in an inconspicuous corner

definitions: causing trouble, difficulties, or discomfort by not fitting well with plans or needs
examples: The meeting was scheduled at an inconvenient time
Living far from work proved inconvenient for commuting

definitions: included as an integral part of something larger or combined with it
legally established as a corporation with formal business structure
examples: The new features were incorporated into the design
All feedback was incorporated into the final report
The incorporated business could now issue stock shares
They formed an incorporated company for tax benefits

definitions: not in accordance with fact or truth containing errors or mistakes
examples: The incorrect answer cost him points on the test
She gave an incorrect address for the delivery

definitions: not able to be morally corrupted or bribed especially by maintaining strong ethical principles
examples: The judge had an incorruptible reputation for fairness
She remained incorruptible despite numerous bribe attempts

definitions: unable or unwilling to believe something often showing doubt or skepticism
examples: She gave him an incredulous look when he explained
The audience was incredulous about the speaker's claims

definitions: relating to or denoting an increase or addition especially occurring in regular small amounts
examples: The company made incremental improvements each quarter
Learning a language requires incremental progress over time

definitions: making someone appear guilty of a crime or wrongdoing by providing evidence against them
examples: The detective found incriminating evidence at the scene
His incriminating emails were used against him in court

definitions: currently holding a specified office or position especially in politics or business
necessary for someone as a duty or responsibility that should be fulfilled
examples: The incumbent mayor faced several challengers in election
The incumbent CEO announced plans for retirement
It is incumbent upon us to help those in need
She felt it incumbent to report the safety violation

definitions: not able to be cured or healed especially referring to diseases or conditions
examples: The doctor diagnosed him with an incurable disease
Her incurable optimism brightened everyone's day

definitions: owing money to someone or having financial obligations to pay back
owing gratitude for a service or favor received from someone
examples: The company was heavily indebted to several banks
Students often graduate indebted from their education loans
I am deeply indebted to you for your kindness
She felt indebted to her mentor for career guidance

definitions: not conforming with generally accepted standards of behavior or morality especially regarding sexuality
examples: His indecent proposal shocked everyone at the meeting
The movie was rated for indecent content and language

definitions: not able to make decisions quickly and effectively often wavering between choices
examples: Her indecisive nature made shopping trips last hours
The indecisive leader lost support from his team

definitions: persisting tirelessly with sustained effort and energy never seeming to get tired
examples: The indefatigable volunteer worked through the entire weekend
Her indefatigable spirit inspired the whole team to continue

definitions: not justifiable by argument or able to be defended against criticism or attack
examples: His actions were morally indefensible and widely condemned
The company's indefensible policies led to public backlash

definitions: lasting for an unknown or unstated length of time without clear limits
examples: She took an indefinite leave from her job
The project was postponed for an indefinite period

definitions: making marks that cannot be removed or forgotten leaving permanent impressions
examples: The experience left an indelible mark on her memory
He wrote with indelible ink to prevent forgery

definitions: bound by a contract to work for another person for a specified time
examples: Indentured servants worked to pay off their passage
The indentured apprentice learned skills from the master

definitions: too unusual, extreme, or indefinite to be adequately described in words
examples: The sunset's beauty was indescribable in its magnificence
She felt indescribable joy when her child was born

definitions: not able to be destroyed or so strong that it seems impossible to break
examples: The safe was made of seemingly indestructible material
Their friendship proved indestructible despite many challenges

definitions: not exactly known, established, or defined with unclear boundaries or limits
examples: The fossil's age remained indeterminate without proper testing
He faced an indeterminate sentence pending further review

definitions: serving as a sign or indication of something suggesting its nature or existence
examples: Her symptoms were indicative of a viral infection
The data is indicative of improving economic conditions

definitions: liable to be accused or charged with a crime serious enough for formal prosecution
examples: The fraud constituted an indictable offense under law
His actions were deemed indictable by the grand jury

definitions: produced independently from major commercial companies especially in music, film, or publishing
examples: The indie film won awards at several festivals
She preferred indie music to mainstream pop songs

definitions: having no particular interest or sympathy showing lack of concern or care
neither good nor bad being mediocre or unremarkable in quality
examples: He seemed indifferent to her emotional distress yesterday
The voters were indifferent to the candidate's message
The restaurant served indifferent food at high prices
Her indifferent performance disappointed the demanding audience

definitions: poor and needy lacking money and resources to provide for oneself
examples: The charity provides medical care for indigent patients
Legal aid helps indigent defendants get proper representation

definitions: feeling or showing anger or annoyance at perceived unfair treatment or injustice
examples: She was indignant about the false accusations made
The crowd grew indignant over the unfair decision

definitions: having a deep purplish-blue color like the dye obtained from certain plants
examples: She wore an indigo dress to the evening gala
The indigo sky signaled the approaching storm clouds

definitions: not directly caused by or resulting from something taking a roundabout path or approach
examples: She took an indirect route to avoid traffic
His indirect criticism was still clearly understood

definitions: done at random or without careful judgment not making careful distinctions between things
examples: The indiscriminate bombing destroyed civilian and military targets
His indiscriminate spending habits led to financial trouble

definitions: absolutely necessary or essential that cannot be done without or dispensed with
examples: Water is indispensable for human survival on Earth
She became indispensable to the company's daily operations

definitions: unable to be challenged or denied being unquestionably true with clear evidence
examples: The video provided indisputable proof of his innocence
Her talent was indisputable after the stunning performance

definitions: not clear or sharply defined being vague, blurred, or difficult to perceive
examples: The distant mountains appeared indistinct through the fog
She heard indistinct voices coming from the hallway

definitions: relating to or characteristic of someone who is independent and self-reliant in thought and action
examples: His individualist approach often clashed with team policies
The artist maintained an individualist style throughout career

definitions: marked by or expressing individuality and independence rather than collective action or thought
examples: American culture is often described as highly individualistic
Her individualistic personality made her stand out everywhere

definitions: adapted or designed to meet the particular needs or circumstances of a specific person
examples: The school offered individualized learning plans for students
Each patient received individualized treatment based on needs

definitions: unable to be divided or separated into parts remaining as one complete whole
examples: They believed justice and freedom were indivisible concepts
The nation must remain indivisible despite regional differences

definitions: impossible to subdue or defeat showing a determination that cannot be broken
examples: Her indomitable spirit helped her overcome every obstacle
The team's indomitable will led them to victory

definitions: situated, conducted, or used inside a building or under cover rather than outdoors
examples: The hotel features an indoor swimming pool facility
Indoor plants need different care than outdoor varieties

definitions: brought about or caused deliberately rather than occurring naturally or spontaneously
examples: The doctor performed an induced labor for safety
His induced coma helped his brain heal properly

definitions: characterized by the inference of general laws from particular instances in reasoning or argument
examples: Scientists use inductive reasoning to form new hypotheses
The inductive method starts with observations of phenomena

definitions: having or indicating a tendency to be overly generous to or lenient with someone
examples: The indulgent parents rarely disciplined their spoiled children
He was indulgent with himself when choosing desserts

definitions: having developed industries on a wide scale with mechanized production and manufacturing
examples: Britain became industrialised during the nineteenth century rapidly
Industrialised nations face different challenges than developing ones

definitions: having developed industries on a wide scale with mechanized production and manufacturing
examples: Japan rapidly industrialized after the Meiji Restoration period
Industrialized countries consume more resources per capita overall

definitions: diligent and hard-working showing dedication and effort in one's work or duties
examples: The industrious student completed all assignments ahead of schedule
Her industrious nature impressed all of her employers

definitions: drunk or intoxicated by alcohol affecting one's mental and physical control
examples: The inebriated guest had to be escorted home
Police arrested several inebriated drivers during the checkpoint
